  "doc_id": "19085",
  "text": "In this study, we examined the association between neuromotor attainments and sleep-wake regulation in a heterogeneous sample and found that (a) overall the sleep difficulties were not related to the child's neuromotor achievements, and (b) the degree of risk, as defined by a cumulative risk index that represented pre-and post-natal indicators, was only mildly associated with the infants' sleep patterns. Upon examining the predictive validity of the risk indicators to sleep problems, we found that that the index explained a very small, albeit statistically significant, portion of the sleep variance. A number of explanations are possible. The first is that since sleep-wake regulation in the first year is a robust process which is governed primarily by biological rhythms [CITATION_1] , variations in child variables (such as birth weight or gestational age) and maternal factors (such as health or age) have only small impacts on infants' sleep [CITATION_2] . It is also possible that the sleep of infants assigned to the three groups differed in ways that our methodology failed to tap. A future study that applies objective sleep recordings could address the sleep-wake rhythms and structure of infants at risk for neuromotor delays with comparative samples.",
